250/*
251 * topdown events for Intel Core CPUs.
252 *
253 * The events are all in slots, which is a free slot in a 4 wide
254 * pipeline. Some events are already reported in slots, for cycle
255 * events we multiply by the pipeline width (4).
256 *
257 * With Hyper Threading on, topdown metrics are either summed or averaged
258 * between the threads of a core: (count_t0 + count_t1).
259 *
260 * For the average case the metric is always scaled to pipeline width,
261 * so we use factor 2 ((count_t0 + count_t1) / 2 * 4)
262 */
263
264EVENT_ATTR_STR_HT(topdown-total-slots, td_total_slots,
265 "event=0x3c,umask=0x0", /* cpu_clk_unhalted.thread */
266 "event=0x3c,umask=0x0,any=1"); /* cpu_clk_unhalted.thread_any */
267EVENT_ATTR_STR_HT(topdown-total-slots.scale, td_total_slots_scale, "4", "2");
268EVENT_ATTR_STR(topdown-slots-issued, td_slots_issued,
269 "event=0xe,umask=0x1"); /* uops_issued.any */
270EVENT_ATTR_STR(topdown-slots-retired, td_slots_retired,
271 "event=0xc2,umask=0x2"); /* uops_retired.retire_slots */
272EVENT_ATTR_STR(topdown-fetch-bubbles, td_fetch_bubbles,
273 "event=0x9c,umask=0x1"); /* idq_uops_not_delivered_core */
274EVENT_ATTR_STR_HT(topdown-recovery-bubbles, td_recovery_bubbles,
275 "event=0xd,umask=0x3,cmask=1", /* int_misc.recovery_cycles */
276 "event=0xd,umask=0x3,cmask=1,any=1"); /* int_misc.recovery_cycles_any */
277EVENT_ATTR_STR_HT(topdown-recovery-bubbles.scale, td_recovery_bubbles_scale,
278 "4", "2");

340/*
341 * Notes on the events:
342 * - data reads do not include code reads (comparable to earlier tables)
343 * - data counts include speculative execution (except L1 write, dtlb, bpu)
344 * - remote node access includes remote memory, remote cache, remote mmio.
345 * - prefetches are not included in the counts.
346 * - icache miss does not include decoded icache
347 */
348
349#define SKL_DEMAND_DATA_RD BIT_ULL(0)
350#define SKL_DEMAND_RFO BIT_ULL(1)
351#define SKL_ANY_RESPONSE BIT_ULL(16)
352#define SKL_SUPPLIER_NONE BIT_ULL(17)
353#define SKL_L3_MISS_LOCAL_DRAM BIT_ULL(26)
354#define SKL_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP0_DRAM BIT_ULL(27)
355#define SKL_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP1_DRAM BIT_ULL(28)
356#define SKL_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP2P_DRAM BIT_ULL(29)
357#define SKL_L3_MISS (SKL_L3_MISS_LOCAL_DRAM| \
358 SKL_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP0_DRAM| \
359 SKL_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP1_DRAM| \
360 SKL_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP2P_DRAM)
361#define SKL_SPL_HIT BIT_ULL(30)
362#define SKL_SNOOP_NONE BIT_ULL(31)
363#define SKL_SNOOP_NOT_NEEDED BIT_ULL(32)
364#define SKL_SNOOP_MISS BIT_ULL(33)
365#define SKL_SNOOP_HIT_NO_FWD BIT_ULL(34)
366#define SKL_SNOOP_HIT_WITH_FWD BIT_ULL(35)
367#define SKL_SNOOP_HITM BIT_ULL(36)
368#define SKL_SNOOP_NON_DRAM BIT_ULL(37)
369#define SKL_ANY_SNOOP (SKL_SPL_HIT|SKL_SNOOP_NONE| \
370 SKL_SNOOP_NOT_NEEDED|SKL_SNOOP_MISS| \
371 SKL_SNOOP_HIT_NO_FWD|SKL_SNOOP_HIT_WITH_FWD| \
372 SKL_SNOOP_HITM|SKL_SNOOP_NON_DRAM)
373#define SKL_DEMAND_READ SKL_DEMAND_DATA_RD
374#define SKL_SNOOP_DRAM (SKL_SNOOP_NONE| \
375 SKL_SNOOP_NOT_NEEDED|SKL_SNOOP_MISS| \
376 SKL_SNOOP_HIT_NO_FWD|SKL_SNOOP_HIT_WITH_FWD| \
377 SKL_SNOOP_HITM|SKL_SPL_HIT)
378#define SKL_DEMAND_WRITE SKL_DEMAND_RFO
379#define SKL_LLC_ACCESS SKL_ANY_RESPONSE
380#define SKL_L3_MISS_REMOTE (SKL_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP0_DRAM| \
381 SKL_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP1_DRAM| \
382 SKL_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP2P_DRAM)

724/*
725 * Notes on the events:
726 * - data reads do not include code reads (comparable to earlier tables)
727 * - data counts include speculative execution (except L1 write, dtlb, bpu)
728 * - remote node access includes remote memory, remote cache, remote mmio.
729 * - prefetches are not included in the counts because they are not
730 * reliably counted.
731 */
732
733#define HSW_DEMAND_DATA_RD BIT_ULL(0)
734#define HSW_DEMAND_RFO BIT_ULL(1)
735#define HSW_ANY_RESPONSE BIT_ULL(16)
736#define HSW_SUPPLIER_NONE BIT_ULL(17)
737#define HSW_L3_MISS_LOCAL_DRAM BIT_ULL(22)
738#define HSW_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP0 BIT_ULL(27)
739#define HSW_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP1 BIT_ULL(28)
740#define HSW_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP2P BIT_ULL(29)
741#define HSW_L3_MISS (HSW_L3_MISS_LOCAL_DRAM| \
742 HSW_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP0|HSW_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP1| \
743 HSW_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP2P)
744#define HSW_SNOOP_NONE BIT_ULL(31)
745#define HSW_SNOOP_NOT_NEEDED BIT_ULL(32)
746#define HSW_SNOOP_MISS BIT_ULL(33)
747#define HSW_SNOOP_HIT_NO_FWD BIT_ULL(34)
748#define HSW_SNOOP_HIT_WITH_FWD BIT_ULL(35)
749#define HSW_SNOOP_HITM BIT_ULL(36)
750#define HSW_SNOOP_NON_DRAM BIT_ULL(37)
751#define HSW_ANY_SNOOP (HSW_SNOOP_NONE| \
752 HSW_SNOOP_NOT_NEEDED|HSW_SNOOP_MISS| \
753 HSW_SNOOP_HIT_NO_FWD|HSW_SNOOP_HIT_WITH_FWD| \
754 HSW_SNOOP_HITM|HSW_SNOOP_NON_DRAM)
755#define HSW_SNOOP_DRAM (HSW_ANY_SNOOP & ~HSW_SNOOP_NON_DRAM)
756#define HSW_DEMAND_READ HSW_DEMAND_DATA_RD
757#define HSW_DEMAND_WRITE HSW_DEMAND_RFO
758#define HSW_L3_MISS_REMOTE (HSW_L3_MISS_REMOTE_HOP0|\

1035/*
1036 * Nehalem/Westmere MSR_OFFCORE_RESPONSE bits;

1040#define NHM_DMND_DATA_RD (1 << 0)
1041#define NHM_DMND_RFO (1 << 1)
1042#define NHM_DMND_IFETCH (1 << 2)
1043#define NHM_DMND_WB (1 << 3)
1044#define NHM_PF_DATA_RD (1 << 4)
1045#define NHM_PF_DATA_RFO (1 << 5)
1046#define NHM_PF_IFETCH (1 << 6)

1048#define NHM_UNCORE_HIT (1 << 8)
1049#define NHM_OTHER_CORE_HIT_SNP (1 << 9)
1050#define NHM_OTHER_CORE_HITM (1 << 10)
1051 /* reserved */
1052#define NHM_REMOTE_CACHE_FWD (1 << 12)
1053#define NHM_REMOTE_DRAM (1 << 13)
1054#define NHM_LOCAL_DRAM (1 << 14)
1055#define NHM_NON_DRAM (1 << 15)
1056
1057#define NHM_LOCAL (NHM_LOCAL_DRAM|NHM_REMOTE_CACHE_FWD)
1058#define NHM_REMOTE (NHM_REMOTE_DRAM)
1059
1060#define NHM_DMND_READ (NHM_DMND_DATA_RD)
1061#define NHM_DMND_WRITE (NHM_DMND_RFO|NHM_DMND_WB)
1062#define NHM_DMND_PREFETCH (NHM_PF_DATA_RD|NHM_PF_DATA_RFO)
1063
1064#define NHM_L3_HIT (NHM_UNCORE_HIT|NHM_OTHER_CORE_HIT_SNP|NHM_OTHER_CORE_HITM)
1065#define NHM_L3_MISS (NHM_NON_DRAM|NHM_LOCAL_DRAM|NHM_REMOTE_DRAM|NHM_REMOTE_CACHE_FWD)
1066#define NHM_L3_ACCESS (NHM_L3_HIT|NHM_L3_MISS)

1861/*
1862 * Used from PMIs where the LBRs are already disabled.
1863 *
1864 * This function could be called consecutively. It is required to remain in
1865 * disabled state if called consecutively.
1866 *
1867 * During consecutive calls, the same disable value will be written to related
1868 * registers, so the PMU state remains unchanged.
1869 *
1870 * intel_bts events don't coexist with intel PMU's BTS events because of
1871 * x86_add_exclusive(x86_lbr_exclusive_lbr); there's no need to keep them
1872 * disabled around intel PMU's event batching etc, only inside the PMI handler.
1873 */
1874static void __intel_pmu_disable_all(void)
1875{
1876 struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc = this_cpu_ptr(&cpu_hw_events);
1877
1878 wrmsrl(MSR_CORE_PERF_GLOBAL_CTRL, 0);
1879
1880 if (test_bit(INTEL_PMC_IDX_FIXED_BTS, cpuc->active_mask))
1881 intel_pmu_disable_bts();
1882
1883 intel_pmu_pebs_disable_all();
1884}
1885
1886static void intel_pmu_disable_all(void)
1887{
1888 __intel_pmu_disable_all();
1889 intel_pmu_lbr_disable_all();
1890}
1891
1892static void __intel_pmu_enable_all(int added, bool pmi)
1893{
1894 struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc = this_cpu_ptr(&cpu_hw_events);
1895
1896 intel_pmu_pebs_enable_all();
1897 intel_pmu_lbr_enable_all(pmi);
1898 wrmsrl(MSR_CORE_PERF_GLOBAL_CTRL,
1899 x86_pmu.intel_ctrl & ~cpuc->intel_ctrl_guest_mask);
1900
1901 if (test_bit(INTEL_PMC_IDX_FIXED_BTS, cpuc->active_mask)) {
1902 struct perf_event *event =
1903 cpuc->events[INTEL_PMC_IDX_FIXED_BTS];
1904
1905 if (WARN_ON_ONCE(!event))
1906 return;
1907
1908 intel_pmu_enable_bts(event->hw.config);
1909 }
1910}
1911
1912static void intel_pmu_enable_all(int added)
1913{
1914 __intel_pmu_enable_all(added, false);
1915}

1917/*
1918 * Workaround for:
1919 * Intel Errata AAK100 (model 26)
1920 * Intel Errata AAP53 (model 30)
1921 * Intel Errata BD53 (model 44)
1922 *
1923 * The official story:
1924 * These chips need to be 'reset' when adding counters by programming the
1925 * magic three (non-counting) events 0x4300B5, 0x4300D2, and 0x4300B1 either
1926 * in sequence on the same PMC or on different PMCs.
1927 *
1928 * In practise it appears some of these events do in fact count, and
1929 * we need to programm all 4 events.
1930 */
1931static void intel_pmu_nhm_workaround(void)
1932{
1933 struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc = this_cpu_ptr(&cpu_hw_events);
1934 static const unsigned long nhm_magic[4] = {
1935 0x4300B5,
1936 0x4300D2,
1937 0x4300B1,
1938 0x4300B1
1939 };
1940 struct perf_event *event;
1941 int i;
1942
1943 /*
1944 * The Errata requires below steps:
1945 * 1) Clear MSR_IA32_PEBS_ENABLE and MSR_CORE_PERF_GLOBAL_CTRL;
1946 * 2) Configure 4 PERFEVTSELx with the magic events and clear
1947 * the corresponding PMCx;
1948 * 3) set bit0~bit3 of MSR_CORE_PERF_GLOBAL_CTRL;
1949 * 4) Clear MSR_CORE_PERF_GLOBAL_CTRL;
1950 * 5) Clear 4 pairs of ERFEVTSELx and PMCx;
1951 */
1952
1953 /*
1954 * The real steps we choose are a little different from above.
1955 * A) To reduce MSR operations, we don't run step 1) as they
1956 * are already cleared before this function is called;
1957 * B) Call x86_perf_event_update to save PMCx before configuring
1958 * PERFEVTSELx with magic number;
1959 * C) With step 5), we do clear only when the PERFEVTSELx is
1960 * not used currently.
1961 * D) Call x86_perf_event_set_period to restore PMCx;
1962 */
1963
1964 /* We always operate 4 pairs of PERF Counters */
1965 for (i = 0; i < 4; i++) {
1966 event = cpuc->events[i];
1967 if (event)
1968 x86_perf_event_update(event);
1969 }
1970
1971 for (i = 0; i < 4; i++) {
1972 wrmsrl(MSR_ARCH_PERFMON_EVENTSEL0 + i, nhm_magic[i]);
1973 wrmsrl(MSR_ARCH_PERFMON_PERFCTR0 + i, 0x0);
1974 }
1975
1976 wrmsrl(MSR_CORE_PERF_GLOBAL_CTRL, 0xf);
1977 wrmsrl(MSR_CORE_PERF_GLOBAL_CTRL, 0x0);
1978
1979 for (i = 0; i < 4; i++) {
1980 event = cpuc->events[i];
1981
1982 if (event) {
1983 x86_perf_event_set_period(event);
1984 __x86_pmu_enable_event(&event->hw,
1985 ARCH_PERFMON_EVENTSEL_ENABLE);
1986 } else
1987 wrmsrl(MSR_ARCH_PERFMON_EVENTSEL0 + i, 0x0);
1988 }
1989}
1990
1991static void intel_pmu_nhm_enable_all(int added)
1992{
1993 if (added)
1994 intel_pmu_nhm_workaround();
1995 intel_pmu_enable_all(added);
1996}

2012static void intel_pmu_disable_fixed(struct hw_perf_event *hwc)
2013{
2014 int idx = hwc->idx - INTEL_PMC_IDX_FIXED;
2015 u64 ctrl_val, mask;
2016
2017 mask = 0xfULL << (idx * 4);
2018
2019 rdmsrl(hwc->config_base, ctrl_val);
2020 ctrl_val &= ~mask;
2021 wrmsrl(hwc->config_base, ctrl_val);
2022}

2028
2029static void intel_pmu_disable_event(struct perf_event *event)
2030{
2031 struct hw_perf_event *hwc = &event->hw;
2032 struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc = this_cpu_ptr(&cpu_hw_events);
2033
2034 if (unlikely(hwc->idx == INTEL_PMC_IDX_FIXED_BTS)) {
2035 intel_pmu_disable_bts();
2036 intel_pmu_drain_bts_buffer();
2037 return;
2038 }
2039
2040 cpuc->intel_ctrl_guest_mask &= ~(1ull << hwc->idx);
2041 cpuc->intel_ctrl_host_mask &= ~(1ull << hwc->idx);
2042 cpuc->intel_cp_status &= ~(1ull << hwc->idx);
2043
2044 if (unlikely(hwc->config_base == MSR_ARCH_PERFMON_FIXED_CTR_CTRL)) {
2045 intel_pmu_disable_fixed(hwc);
2046 return;
2047 }
2048
2049 x86_pmu_disable_event(event);
2050
2051 if (unlikely(event->attr.precise_ip))
2052 intel_pmu_pebs_disable(event);
2053}
2054
2055static void intel_pmu_del_event(struct perf_event *event)
2056{
2057 if (needs_branch_stack(event))
2058 intel_pmu_lbr_del(event);
2059 if (event->attr.precise_ip)
2060 intel_pmu_pebs_del(event);
2061}
2062
2063static void intel_pmu_enable_fixed(struct hw_perf_event *hwc)
2064{
2065 int idx = hwc->idx - INTEL_PMC_IDX_FIXED;
2066 u64 ctrl_val, bits, mask;
2067
2068 /*
2069 * Enable IRQ generation (0x8),
2070 * and enable ring-3 counting (0x2) and ring-0 counting (0x1)
2071 * if requested:
2072 */
2073 bits = 0x8ULL;
2074 if (hwc->config & ARCH_PERFMON_EVENTSEL_USR)
2075 bits |= 0x2;
2076 if (hwc->config & ARCH_PERFMON_EVENTSEL_OS)
2077 bits |= 0x1;
2078
2079 /*
2080 * ANY bit is supported in v3 and up
2081 */
2082 if (x86_pmu.version > 2 && hwc->config & ARCH_PERFMON_EVENTSEL_ANY)
2083 bits |= 0x4;
2084
2085 bits <<= (idx * 4);
2086 mask = 0xfULL << (idx * 4);
2087
2088 rdmsrl(hwc->config_base, ctrl_val);
2089 ctrl_val &= ~mask;
2090 ctrl_val |= bits;
2091 wrmsrl(hwc->config_base, ctrl_val);
2092}
2093
2094static void intel_pmu_enable_event(struct perf_event *event)
2095{
2096 struct hw_perf_event *hwc = &event->hw;
2097 struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc = this_cpu_ptr(&cpu_hw_events);
2098
2099 if (unlikely(hwc->idx == INTEL_PMC_IDX_FIXED_BTS)) {
2100 if (!__this_cpu_read(cpu_hw_events.enabled))
2101 return;
2102
2103 intel_pmu_enable_bts(hwc->config);
2104 return;
2105 }
2106
2107 if (event->attr.exclude_host)
2108 cpuc->intel_ctrl_guest_mask |= (1ull << hwc->idx);
2109 if (event->attr.exclude_guest)
2110 cpuc->intel_ctrl_host_mask |= (1ull << hwc->idx);
2111
2112 if (unlikely(event_is_checkpointed(event)))
2113 cpuc->intel_cp_status |= (1ull << hwc->idx);
2114
2115 if (unlikely(hwc->config_base == MSR_ARCH_PERFMON_FIXED_CTR_CTRL)) {
2116 intel_pmu_enable_fixed(hwc);
2117 return;
2118 }
2119
2120 if (unlikely(event->attr.precise_ip))
2121 intel_pmu_pebs_enable(event);
2122
2123 __x86_pmu_enable_event(hwc, ARCH_PERFMON_EVENTSEL_ENABLE);
2124}
2125
2126static void intel_pmu_add_event(struct perf_event *event)
2127{
2128 if (event->attr.precise_ip)
2129 intel_pmu_pebs_add(event);
2130 if (needs_branch_stack(event))
2131 intel_pmu_lbr_add(event);
2132}
2133
2134/*
2135 * Save and restart an expired event. Called by NMI contexts,
2136 * so it has to be careful about preempting normal event ops:
2137 */
2138int intel_pmu_save_and_restart(struct perf_event *event)
2139{
2140 x86_perf_event_update(event);
2141 /*
2142 * For a checkpointed counter always reset back to 0. This
2143 * avoids a situation where the counter overflows, aborts the
2144 * transaction and is then set back to shortly before the
2145 * overflow, and overflows and aborts again.
2146 */
2147 if (unlikely(event_is_checkpointed(event))) {
2148 /* No race with NMIs because the counter should not be armed */
2149 wrmsrl(event->hw.event_base, 0);
2150 local64_set(&event->hw.prev_count, 0);
2151 }
2152 return x86_perf_event_set_period(event);
2153}
2154
2155static void intel_pmu_reset(void)
2156{
2157 struct debug_store *ds = __this_cpu_read(cpu_hw_events.ds);
2158 unsigned long flags;
2159 int idx;
2160
2161 if (!x86_pmu.num_counters)
2162 return;
2163
2164 local_irq_save(flags);
2165
2166 pr_info("clearing PMU state on CPU#%d\n", smp_processor_id());
2167
2168 for (idx = 0; idx < x86_pmu.num_counters; idx++) {
2169 wrmsrl_safe(x86_pmu_config_addr(idx), 0ull);
2170 wrmsrl_safe(x86_pmu_event_addr(idx), 0ull);
2171 }
2172 for (idx = 0; idx < x86_pmu.num_counters_fixed; idx++)
2173 wrmsrl_safe(MSR_ARCH_PERFMON_FIXED_CTR0 + idx, 0ull);
2174
2175 if (ds)
2176 ds->bts_index = ds->bts_buffer_base;
2177
2178 /* Ack all overflows and disable fixed counters */
2179 if (x86_pmu.version >= 2) {
2180 intel_pmu_ack_status(intel_pmu_get_status());
2181 wrmsrl(MSR_CORE_PERF_GLOBAL_CTRL, 0);
2182 }
2183
2184 /* Reset LBRs and LBR freezing */
2185 if (x86_pmu.lbr_nr) {
2186 update_debugctlmsr(get_debugctlmsr() &
2187 ~(DEBUGCTLMSR_FREEZE_LBRS_ON_PMI|DEBUGCTLMSR_LBR));
2188 }
2189
2190 local_irq_restore(flags);
2191}
2192
2193/*
2194 * This handler is triggered by the local APIC, so the APIC IRQ handling
2195 * rules apply:
2196 */
2197static int intel_pmu_handle_irq(struct pt_regs *regs)
2198{
2199 struct perf_sample_data data;
2200 struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc;
2201 int bit, loops;
2202 u64 status;
2203 int handled;
2204 int pmu_enabled;
2205
2206 cpuc = this_cpu_ptr(&cpu_hw_events);
2207
2208 /*
2209 * Save the PMU state.
2210 * It needs to be restored when leaving the handler.
2211 */
2212 pmu_enabled = cpuc->enabled;
2213 /*
2214 * No known reason to not always do late ACK,
2215 * but just in case do it opt-in.
2216 */
2217 if (!x86_pmu.late_ack)
2218 apic_write(APIC_LVTPC, APIC_DM_NMI);
2219 intel_bts_disable_local();
2220 cpuc->enabled = 0;
2221 __intel_pmu_disable_all();
2222 handled = intel_pmu_drain_bts_buffer();
2223 handled += intel_bts_interrupt();
2224 status = intel_pmu_get_status();
2225 if (!status)
2226 goto done;
2227
2228 loops = 0;
2229again:
2230 intel_pmu_lbr_read();
2231 intel_pmu_ack_status(status);
2232 if (++loops > 100) {
2233 static bool warned = false;
2234 if (!warned) {
2235 WARN(1, "perfevents: irq loop stuck!\n");
2236 perf_event_print_debug();
2237 warned = true;
2238 }
2239 intel_pmu_reset();
2240 goto done;
2241 }
2242
2243 inc_irq_stat(apic_perf_irqs);
2244
2245
2246 /*
2247 * Ignore a range of extra bits in status that do not indicate
2248 * overflow by themselves.
2249 */
2250 status &= ~(GLOBAL_STATUS_COND_CHG |
2251 GLOBAL_STATUS_ASIF |
2252 GLOBAL_STATUS_LBRS_FROZEN);
2253 if (!status)
2254 goto done;
2255 /*
2256 * In case multiple PEBS events are sampled at the same time,
2257 * it is possible to have GLOBAL_STATUS bit 62 set indicating
2258 * PEBS buffer overflow and also seeing at most 3 PEBS counters
2259 * having their bits set in the status register. This is a sign
2260 * that there was at least one PEBS record pending at the time
2261 * of the PMU interrupt. PEBS counters must only be processed
2262 * via the drain_pebs() calls and not via the regular sample
2263 * processing loop coming after that the function, otherwise
2264 * phony regular samples may be generated in the sampling buffer
2265 * not marked with the EXACT tag. Another possibility is to have
2266 * one PEBS event and at least one non-PEBS event whic hoverflows
2267 * while PEBS has armed. In this case, bit 62 of GLOBAL_STATUS will
2268 * not be set, yet the overflow status bit for the PEBS counter will
2269 * be on Skylake.
2270 *
2271 * To avoid this problem, we systematically ignore the PEBS-enabled
2272 * counters from the GLOBAL_STATUS mask and we always process PEBS
2273 * events via drain_pebs().
2274 */
2275 status &= ~(cpuc->pebs_enabled & PEBS_COUNTER_MASK);
2276
2277 /*
2278 * PEBS overflow sets bit 62 in the global status register
2279 */
2280 if (__test_and_clear_bit(62, (unsigned long *)&status)) {
2281 handled++;
2282 x86_pmu.drain_pebs(regs);
2283 status &= x86_pmu.intel_ctrl | GLOBAL_STATUS_TRACE_TOPAPMI;
2284 }
2285
2286 /*
2287 * Intel PT
2288 */
2289 if (__test_and_clear_bit(55, (unsigned long *)&status)) {
2290 handled++;
2291 intel_pt_interrupt();
2292 }
2293
2294 /*
2295 * Checkpointed counters can lead to 'spurious' PMIs because the
2296 * rollback caused by the PMI will have cleared the overflow status
2297 * bit. Therefore always force probe these counters.
2298 */
2299 status |= cpuc->intel_cp_status;
2300
2301 for_each_set_bit(bit, (unsigned long *)&status, X86_PMC_IDX_MAX) {
2302 struct perf_event *event = cpuc->events[bit];
2303
2304 handled++;
2305
2306 if (!test_bit(bit, cpuc->active_mask))
2307 continue;
2308
2309 if (!intel_pmu_save_and_restart(event))
2310 continue;
2311
2312 perf_sample_data_init(&data, 0, event->hw.last_period);
2313
2314 if (has_branch_stack(event))
2315 data.br_stack = &cpuc->lbr_stack;
2316
2317 if (perf_event_overflow(event, &data, regs))
2318 x86_pmu_stop(event, 0);
2319 }
2320
2321 /*
2322 * Repeat if there is more work to be done:
2323 */
2324 status = intel_pmu_get_status();
2325 if (status)
2326 goto again;
2327
2328done:
2329 /* Only restore PMU state when it's active. See x86_pmu_disable(). */
2330 cpuc->enabled = pmu_enabled;
2331 if (pmu_enabled)
2332 __intel_pmu_enable_all(0, true);
2333 intel_bts_enable_local();
2334
2335 /*
2336 * Only unmask the NMI after the overflow counters
2337 * have been reset. This avoids spurious NMIs on
2338 * Haswell CPUs.
2339 */
2340 if (x86_pmu.late_ack)
2341 apic_write(APIC_LVTPC, APIC_DM_NMI);
2342 return handled;
2343}

2345static struct event_constraint *
2346intel_bts_constraints(struct perf_event *event)
2347{
2348 struct hw_perf_event *hwc = &event->hw;
2349 unsigned int hw_event, bts_event;
2350
2351 if (event->attr.freq)
2352 return NULL;
2353
2354 hw_event = hwc->config & INTEL_ARCH_EVENT_MASK;
2355 bts_event = x86_pmu.event_map(PERF_COUNT_HW_BRANCH_INSTRUCTIONS);
2356
2357 if (unlikely(hw_event == bts_event && hwc->sample_period == 1))
2358 return &bts_constraint;
2359
2360 return NULL;
2361}
2362
2363static int intel_alt_er(int idx, u64 config)
2364{
2365 int alt_idx = idx;
2366
2367 if (!(x86_pmu.flags & PMU_FL_HAS_RSP_1))
2368 return idx;
2369
2370 if (idx == EXTRA_REG_RSP_0)
2371 alt_idx = EXTRA_REG_RSP_1;
2372
2373 if (idx == EXTRA_REG_RSP_1)
2374 alt_idx = EXTRA_REG_RSP_0;
2375
2376 if (config & ~x86_pmu.extra_regs[alt_idx].valid_mask)
2377 return idx;
2378
2379 return alt_idx;
2380}
2381
2382static void intel_fixup_er(struct perf_event *event, int idx)
2383{
2384 event->hw.extra_reg.idx = idx;
2385
2386 if (idx == EXTRA_REG_RSP_0) {
2387 event->hw.config &= ~INTEL_ARCH_EVENT_MASK;
2388 event->hw.config |= x86_pmu.extra_regs[EXTRA_REG_RSP_0].event;
2389 event->hw.extra_reg.reg = MSR_OFFCORE_RSP_0;
2390 } else if (idx == EXTRA_REG_RSP_1) {
2391 event->hw.config &= ~INTEL_ARCH_EVENT_MASK;
2392 event->hw.config |= x86_pmu.extra_regs[EXTRA_REG_RSP_1].event;
2393 event->hw.extra_reg.reg = MSR_OFFCORE_RSP_1;
2394 }
2395}
2396
2397/*
2398 * manage allocation of shared extra msr for certain events
2399 *
2400 * sharing can be:
2401 * per-cpu: to be shared between the various events on a single PMU
2402 * per-core: per-cpu + shared by HT threads
2403 */
2404static struct event_constraint *
2405__intel_shared_reg_get_constraints(struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc,
2406 struct perf_event *event,
2407 struct hw_perf_event_extra *reg)
2408{
2409 struct event_constraint *c = &emptyconstraint;
2410 struct er_account *era;
2411 unsigned long flags;
2412 int idx = reg->idx;
2413
2414 /*
2415 * reg->alloc can be set due to existing state, so for fake cpuc we
2416 * need to ignore this, otherwise we might fail to allocate proper fake
2417 * state for this extra reg constraint. Also see the comment below.
2418 */
2419 if (reg->alloc && !cpuc->is_fake)
2420 return NULL; /* call x86_get_event_constraint() */
2421
2422again:
2423 era = &cpuc->shared_regs->regs[idx];
2424 /*
2425 * we use spin_lock_irqsave() to avoid lockdep issues when
2426 * passing a fake cpuc
2427 */
2428 raw_spin_lock_irqsave(&era->lock, flags);
2429
2430 if (!atomic_read(&era->ref) || era->config == reg->config) {
2431
2432 /*
2433 * If its a fake cpuc -- as per validate_{group,event}() we
2434 * shouldn't touch event state and we can avoid doing so
2435 * since both will only call get_event_constraints() once
2436 * on each event, this avoids the need for reg->alloc.
2437 *
2438 * Not doing the ER fixup will only result in era->reg being
2439 * wrong, but since we won't actually try and program hardware
2440 * this isn't a problem either.
2441 */
2442 if (!cpuc->is_fake) {
2443 if (idx != reg->idx)
2444 intel_fixup_er(event, idx);
2445
2446 /*
2447 * x86_schedule_events() can call get_event_constraints()
2448 * multiple times on events in the case of incremental
2449 * scheduling(). reg->alloc ensures we only do the ER
2450 * allocation once.
2451 */
2452 reg->alloc = 1;
2453 }
2454
2455 /* lock in msr value */
2456 era->config = reg->config;
2457 era->reg = reg->reg;
2458
2459 /* one more user */
2460 atomic_inc(&era->ref);
2461
2462 /*
2463 * need to call x86_get_event_constraint()
2464 * to check if associated event has constraints
2465 */
2466 c = NULL;
2467 } else {
2468 idx = intel_alt_er(idx, reg->config);
2469 if (idx != reg->idx) {
2470 raw_spin_unlock_irqrestore(&era->lock, flags);
2471 goto again;
2472 }
2473 }
2474 raw_spin_unlock_irqrestore(&era->lock, flags);
2475
2476 return c;
2477}
2478
2479static void
2480__intel_shared_reg_put_constraints(struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc,
2481 struct hw_perf_event_extra *reg)
2482{
2483 struct er_account *era;
2484
2485 /*
2486 * Only put constraint if extra reg was actually allocated. Also takes
2487 * care of event which do not use an extra shared reg.
2488 *
2489 * Also, if this is a fake cpuc we shouldn't touch any event state
2490 * (reg->alloc) and we don't care about leaving inconsistent cpuc state
2491 * either since it'll be thrown out.
2492 */
2493 if (!reg->alloc || cpuc->is_fake)
2494 return;
2495
2496 era = &cpuc->shared_regs->regs[reg->idx];
2497
2498 /* one fewer user */
2499 atomic_dec(&era->ref);
2500
2501 /* allocate again next time */
2502 reg->alloc = 0;
2503}
2504
2505static struct event_constraint *
2506intel_shared_regs_constraints(struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc,
2507 struct perf_event *event)
2508{
2509 struct event_constraint *c = NULL, *d;
2510 struct hw_perf_event_extra *xreg, *breg;
2511
2512 xreg = &event->hw.extra_reg;
2513 if (xreg->idx != EXTRA_REG_NONE) {
2514 c = __intel_shared_reg_get_constraints(cpuc, event, xreg);
2515 if (c == &emptyconstraint)
2516 return c;
2517 }
2518 breg = &event->hw.branch_reg;
2519 if (breg->idx != EXTRA_REG_NONE) {
2520 d = __intel_shared_reg_get_constraints(cpuc, event, breg);
2521 if (d == &emptyconstraint) {
2522 __intel_shared_reg_put_constraints(cpuc, xreg);
2523 c = d;
2524 }
2525 }
2526 return c;
2527}
2528
2529struct event_constraint *
2530x86_get_event_constraints(struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc, int idx,
2531 struct perf_event *event)
2532{
2533 struct event_constraint *c;
2534
2535 if (x86_pmu.event_constraints) {
2536 for_each_event_constraint(c, x86_pmu.event_constraints) {
2537 if ((event->hw.config & c->cmask) == c->code) {
2538 event->hw.flags |= c->flags;
2539 return c;
2540 }
2541 }
2542 }
2543
2544 return &unconstrained;
2545}

2547static struct event_constraint *
2548__intel_get_event_constraints(struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc, int idx,
2549 struct perf_event *event)
2550{
2551 struct event_constraint *c;
2552
2553 c = intel_bts_constraints(event);
2554 if (c)
2555 return c;
2556
2557 c = intel_shared_regs_constraints(cpuc, event);
2558 if (c)
2559 return c;

2566}

2568static void
2569intel_start_scheduling(struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc)
2570{
2571 struct intel_excl_cntrs *excl_cntrs = cpuc->excl_cntrs;
2572 struct intel_excl_states *xl;
2573 int tid = cpuc->excl_thread_id;
2574
2575 /*
2576 * nothing needed if in group validation mode
2577 */
2578 if (cpuc->is_fake || !is_ht_workaround_enabled())
2579 return;
2580
2581 /*
2582 * no exclusion needed
2583 */
2584 if (WARN_ON_ONCE(!excl_cntrs))
2585 return;
2586
2587 xl = &excl_cntrs->states[tid];
2588
2589 xl->sched_started = true;
2590 /*
2591 * lock shared state until we are done scheduling
2592 * in stop_event_scheduling()
2593 * makes scheduling appear as a transaction
2594 */
2595 raw_spin_lock(&excl_cntrs->lock);
2596}
2597
2598static void intel_commit_scheduling(struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc, int idx, int cntr)
2599{
2600 struct intel_excl_cntrs *excl_cntrs = cpuc->excl_cntrs;
2601 struct event_constraint *c = cpuc->event_constraint[idx];
2602 struct intel_excl_states *xl;
2603 int tid = cpuc->excl_thread_id;
2604
2605 if (cpuc->is_fake || !is_ht_workaround_enabled())
2606 return;
2607
2608 if (WARN_ON_ONCE(!excl_cntrs))
2609 return;
2610
2611 if (!(c->flags & PERF_X86_EVENT_DYNAMIC))
2612 return;
2613
2614 xl = &excl_cntrs->states[tid];
2615
2616 lockdep_assert_held(&excl_cntrs->lock);
2617
2618 if (c->flags & PERF_X86_EVENT_EXCL)
2619 xl->state[cntr] = INTEL_EXCL_EXCLUSIVE;
2620 else
2621 xl->state[cntr] = INTEL_EXCL_SHARED;
2622}
2623
2624static void
2625intel_stop_scheduling(struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc)
2626{
2627 struct intel_excl_cntrs *excl_cntrs = cpuc->excl_cntrs;
2628 struct intel_excl_states *xl;
2629 int tid = cpuc->excl_thread_id;
2630
2631 /*
2632 * nothing needed if in group validation mode
2633 */
2634 if (cpuc->is_fake || !is_ht_workaround_enabled())
2635 return;
2636 /*
2637 * no exclusion needed
2638 */
2639 if (WARN_ON_ONCE(!excl_cntrs))
2640 return;
2641
2642 xl = &excl_cntrs->states[tid];
2643
2644 xl->sched_started = false;
2645 /*
2646 * release shared state lock (acquired in intel_start_scheduling())
2647 */
2648 raw_spin_unlock(&excl_cntrs->lock);
2649}
2650
2651static struct event_constraint *
2652intel_get_excl_constraints(struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc, struct perf_event *event,
2653 int idx, struct event_constraint *c)
2654{
2655 struct intel_excl_cntrs *excl_cntrs = cpuc->excl_cntrs;
2656 struct intel_excl_states *xlo;
2657 int tid = cpuc->excl_thread_id;
2658 int is_excl, i;
2659
2660 /*
2661 * validating a group does not require
2662 * enforcing cross-thread exclusion
2663 */
2664 if (cpuc->is_fake || !is_ht_workaround_enabled())
2665 return c;
2666
2667 /*
2668 * no exclusion needed
2669 */
2670 if (WARN_ON_ONCE(!excl_cntrs))
2671 return c;
2672
2673 /*
2674 * because we modify the constraint, we need
2675 * to make a copy. Static constraints come
2676 * from static const tables.
2677 *
2678 * only needed when constraint has not yet
2679 * been cloned (marked dynamic)
2680 */
2681 if (!(c->flags & PERF_X86_EVENT_DYNAMIC)) {
2682 struct event_constraint *cx;
2683
2684 /*
2685 * grab pre-allocated constraint entry
2686 */
2687 cx = &cpuc->constraint_list[idx];
2688
2689 /*
2690 * initialize dynamic constraint
2691 * with static constraint
2692 */
2693 *cx = *c;
2694
2695 /*
2696 * mark constraint as dynamic, so we
2697 * can free it later on
2698 */
2699 cx->flags |= PERF_X86_EVENT_DYNAMIC;
2700 c = cx;
2701 }
2702
2703 /*
2704 * From here on, the constraint is dynamic.
2705 * Either it was just allocated above, or it
2706 * was allocated during a earlier invocation
2707 * of this function
2708 */
2709
2710 /*
2711 * state of sibling HT
2712 */
2713 xlo = &excl_cntrs->states[tid ^ 1];
2714
2715 /*
2716 * event requires exclusive counter access
2717 * across HT threads
2718 */
2719 is_excl = c->flags & PERF_X86_EVENT_EXCL;
2720 if (is_excl && !(event->hw.flags & PERF_X86_EVENT_EXCL_ACCT)) {
2721 event->hw.flags |= PERF_X86_EVENT_EXCL_ACCT;
2722 if (!cpuc->n_excl++)
2723 WRITE_ONCE(excl_cntrs->has_exclusive[tid], 1);
2724 }
2725
2726 /*
2727 * Modify static constraint with current dynamic
2728 * state of thread
2729 *
2730 * EXCLUSIVE: sibling counter measuring exclusive event
2731 * SHARED : sibling counter measuring non-exclusive event
2732 * UNUSED : sibling counter unused
2733 */
2734 for_each_set_bit(i, c->idxmsk, X86_PMC_IDX_MAX) {
2735 /*
2736 * exclusive event in sibling counter
2737 * our corresponding counter cannot be used
2738 * regardless of our event
2739 */
2740 if (xlo->state[i] == INTEL_EXCL_EXCLUSIVE)
2741 __clear_bit(i, c->idxmsk);
2742 /*
2743 * if measuring an exclusive event, sibling
2744 * measuring non-exclusive, then counter cannot
2745 * be used
2746 */
2747 if (is_excl && xlo->state[i] == INTEL_EXCL_SHARED)
2748 __clear_bit(i, c->idxmsk);
2749 }
2750
2751 /*
2752 * recompute actual bit weight for scheduling algorithm
2753 */
2754 c->weight = hweight64(c->idxmsk64);
2755
2756 /*
2757 * if we return an empty mask, then switch
2758 * back to static empty constraint to avoid
2759 * the cost of freeing later on
2760 */
2761 if (c->weight == 0)
2762 c = &emptyconstraint;
2763
2764 return c;
2765}
2766
2767static struct event_constraint *
2768intel_get_event_constraints(struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc, int idx,
2769 struct perf_event *event)
2770{
2771 struct event_constraint *c1 = NULL;
2772 struct event_constraint *c2;
2773
2774 if (idx >= 0) /* fake does < 0 */
2775 c1 = cpuc->event_constraint[idx];
2776
2777 /*
2778 * first time only
2779 * - static constraint: no change across incremental scheduling calls
2780 * - dynamic constraint: handled by intel_get_excl_constraints()
2781 */
2782 c2 = __intel_get_event_constraints(cpuc, idx, event);
2783 if (c1 && (c1->flags & PERF_X86_EVENT_DYNAMIC)) {
2784 bitmap_copy(c1->idxmsk, c2->idxmsk, X86_PMC_IDX_MAX);
2785 c1->weight = c2->weight;
2786 c2 = c1;
2787 }
2788
2789 if (cpuc->excl_cntrs)
2790 return intel_get_excl_constraints(cpuc, event, idx, c2);
2791
2792 return c2;
2793}
2794
2795static void intel_put_excl_constraints(struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc,
2796 struct perf_event *event)
2797{
2798 struct hw_perf_event *hwc = &event->hw;
2799 struct intel_excl_cntrs *excl_cntrs = cpuc->excl_cntrs;
2800 int tid = cpuc->excl_thread_id;
2801 struct intel_excl_states *xl;
2802
2803 /*
2804 * nothing needed if in group validation mode
2805 */
2806 if (cpuc->is_fake)
2807 return;
2808
2809 if (WARN_ON_ONCE(!excl_cntrs))
2810 return;
2811
2812 if (hwc->flags & PERF_X86_EVENT_EXCL_ACCT) {
2813 hwc->flags &= ~PERF_X86_EVENT_EXCL_ACCT;
2814 if (!--cpuc->n_excl)
2815 WRITE_ONCE(excl_cntrs->has_exclusive[tid], 0);
2816 }
2817
2818 /*
2819 * If event was actually assigned, then mark the counter state as
2820 * unused now.
2821 */
2822 if (hwc->idx >= 0) {
2823 xl = &excl_cntrs->states[tid];
2824
2825 /*
2826 * put_constraint may be called from x86_schedule_events()
2827 * which already has the lock held so here make locking
2828 * conditional.
2829 */
2830 if (!xl->sched_started)
2831 raw_spin_lock(&excl_cntrs->lock);
2832
2833 xl->state[hwc->idx] = INTEL_EXCL_UNUSED;
2834
2835 if (!xl->sched_started)
2836 raw_spin_unlock(&excl_cntrs->lock);
2837 }
2838}

2841intel_put_shared_regs_event_constraints(struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc,
2842 struct perf_event *event)
2843{
2844 struct hw_perf_event_extra *reg;
2845
2846 reg = &event->hw.extra_reg;
2847 if (reg->idx != EXTRA_REG_NONE)

2850 reg = &event->hw.branch_reg;

2869static void intel_pebs_aliases_core2(struct perf_event *event)
2870{
2871 if ((event->hw.config & X86_RAW_EVENT_MASK) == 0x003c) {
2872 /*
2873 * Use an alternative encoding for CPU_CLK_UNHALTED.THREAD_P
2874 * (0x003c) so that we can use it with PEBS.
2875 *
2876 * The regular CPU_CLK_UNHALTED.THREAD_P event (0x003c) isn't
2877 * PEBS capable. However we can use INST_RETIRED.ANY_P
2878 * (0x00c0), which is a PEBS capable event, to get the same
2879 * count.
2880 *
2881 * INST_RETIRED.ANY_P counts the number of cycles that retires
2882 * CNTMASK instructions. By setting CNTMASK to a value (16)
2883 * larger than the maximum number of instructions that can be
2884 * retired per cycle (4) and then inverting the condition, we
2885 * count all cycles that retire 16 or less instructions, which
2886 * is every cycle.
2887 *
2888 * Thereby we gain a PEBS capable cycle counter.
2889 */
2890 u64 alt_config = X86_CONFIG(.event=0xc0, .inv=1, .cmask=16);
2891
2892 alt_config |= (event->hw.config & ~X86_RAW_EVENT_MASK);
2893 event->hw.config = alt_config;
2894 }
2895}
2896
2897static void intel_pebs_aliases_snb(struct perf_event *event)
2898{
2899 if ((event->hw.config & X86_RAW_EVENT_MASK) == 0x003c) {
2900 /*
2901 * Use an alternative encoding for CPU_CLK_UNHALTED.THREAD_P
2902 * (0x003c) so that we can use it with PEBS.
2903 *
2904 * The regular CPU_CLK_UNHALTED.THREAD_P event (0x003c) isn't
2905 * PEBS capable. However we can use UOPS_RETIRED.ALL
2906 * (0x01c2), which is a PEBS capable event, to get the same
2907 * count.
2908 *
2909 * UOPS_RETIRED.ALL counts the number of cycles that retires
2910 * CNTMASK micro-ops. By setting CNTMASK to a value (16)
2911 * larger than the maximum number of micro-ops that can be
2912 * retired per cycle (4) and then inverting the condition, we
2913 * count all cycles that retire 16 or less micro-ops, which
2914 * is every cycle.
2915 *
2916 * Thereby we gain a PEBS capable cycle counter.
2917 */
2918 u64 alt_config = X86_CONFIG(.event=0xc2, .umask=0x01, .inv=1, .cmask=16);
2919
2920 alt_config |= (event->hw.config & ~X86_RAW_EVENT_MASK);
2921 event->hw.config = alt_config;
2922 }
2923}
2924
2925static void intel_pebs_aliases_precdist(struct perf_event *event)
2926{
2927 if ((event->hw.config & X86_RAW_EVENT_MASK) == 0x003c) {
2928 /*
2929 * Use an alternative encoding for CPU_CLK_UNHALTED.THREAD_P
2930 * (0x003c) so that we can use it with PEBS.
2931 *
2932 * The regular CPU_CLK_UNHALTED.THREAD_P event (0x003c) isn't
2933 * PEBS capable. However we can use INST_RETIRED.PREC_DIST
2934 * (0x01c0), which is a PEBS capable event, to get the same
2935 * count.
2936 *
2937 * The PREC_DIST event has special support to minimize sample
2938 * shadowing effects. One drawback is that it can be
2939 * only programmed on counter 1, but that seems like an
2940 * acceptable trade off.
2941 */
2942 u64 alt_config = X86_CONFIG(.event=0xc0, .umask=0x01, .inv=1, .cmask=16);
2943
2944 alt_config |= (event->hw.config & ~X86_RAW_EVENT_MASK);
2945 event->hw.config = alt_config;
2946 }
2947}

2976static int intel_pmu_hw_config(struct perf_event *event)
2977{
2978 int ret = x86_pmu_hw_config(event);
2979
2980 if (ret)
2981 return ret;
2982
2983 if (event->attr.precise_ip) {
2984 if (!event->attr.freq) {
2985 event->hw.flags |= PERF_X86_EVENT_AUTO_RELOAD;
2986 if (!(event->attr.sample_type &
2987 ~intel_pmu_free_running_flags(event)))
2988 event->hw.flags |= PERF_X86_EVENT_FREERUNNING;
2989 }
2990 if (x86_pmu.pebs_aliases)
2991 x86_pmu.pebs_aliases(event);
2992 }
2993
2994 if (needs_branch_stack(event)) {
2995 ret = intel_pmu_setup_lbr_filter(event);
2996 if (ret)
2997 return ret;
2998
2999 /*
3000 * BTS is set up earlier in this path, so don't account twice
3001 */
3002 if (!intel_pmu_has_bts(event)) {
3003 /* disallow lbr if conflicting events are present */
3004 if (x86_add_exclusive(x86_lbr_exclusive_lbr))
3005 return -EBUSY;
3006
3007 event->destroy = hw_perf_lbr_event_destroy;
3008 }
3009 }
3010
3011 if (event->attr.type != PERF_TYPE_RAW)
3012 return 0;
3013
3014 if (!(event->attr.config & ARCH_PERFMON_EVENTSEL_ANY))
3015 return 0;
3016
3017 if (x86_pmu.version < 3)
3018 return -EINVAL;
3019
3020 if (perf_paranoid_cpu() && !capable(CAP_SYS_ADMIN))
3021 return -EACCES;
3022
3023 event->hw.config |= ARCH_PERFMON_EVENTSEL_ANY;
3024
3025 return 0;
3026}

3108static int hsw_hw_config(struct perf_event *event)
3109{
3110 int ret = intel_pmu_hw_config(event);
3111
3112 if (ret)
3113 return ret;
3114 if (!boot_cpu_has(X86_FEATURE_RTM) && !boot_cpu_has(X86_FEATURE_HLE))
3115 return 0;
3116 event->hw.config |= event->attr.config & (HSW_IN_TX|HSW_IN_TX_CHECKPOINTED);
3117
3118 /*
3119 * IN_TX/IN_TX-CP filters are not supported by the Haswell PMU with
3120 * PEBS or in ANY thread mode. Since the results are non-sensical forbid
3121 * this combination.
3122 */
3123 if ((event->hw.config & (HSW_IN_TX|HSW_IN_TX_CHECKPOINTED)) &&
3124 ((event->hw.config & ARCH_PERFMON_EVENTSEL_ANY) ||
3125 event->attr.precise_ip > 0))
3126 return -EOPNOTSUPP;
3127
3128 if (event_is_checkpointed(event)) {
3129 /*
3130 * Sampling of checkpointed events can cause situations where
3131 * the CPU constantly aborts because of a overflow, which is
3132 * then checkpointed back and ignored. Forbid checkpointing
3133 * for sampling.
3134 *
3135 * But still allow a long sampling period, so that perf stat
3136 * from KVM works.
3137 */
3138 if (event->attr.sample_period > 0 &&
3139 event->attr.sample_period < 0x7fffffff)
3140 return -EOPNOTSUPP;
3141 }
3142 return 0;
3143}

3184/*
3185 * Broadwell:
3186 *
3187 * The INST_RETIRED.ALL period always needs to have lowest 6 bits cleared
3188 * (BDM55) and it must not use a period smaller than 100 (BDM11). We combine
3189 * the two to enforce a minimum period of 128 (the smallest value that has bits
3190 * 0-5 cleared and >= 100).
3191 *
3192 * Because of how the code in x86_perf_event_set_period() works, the truncation
3193 * of the lower 6 bits is 'harmless' as we'll occasionally add a longer period
3194 * to make up for the 'lost' events due to carrying the 'error' in period_left.
3195 *
3196 * Therefore the effective (average) period matches the requested period,
3197 * despite coarser hardware granularity.
3198 */
3199static u64 bdw_limit_period(struct perf_event *event, u64 left)
3200{
3201 if ((event->hw.config & INTEL_ARCH_EVENT_MASK) ==
3202 X86_CONFIG(.event=0xc0, .umask=0x01)) {
3203 if (left < 128)
3204 left = 128;
3205 left &= ~0x3fULL;
3206 }
3207 return left;
3208}

3269static int intel_pmu_cpu_prepare(int cpu)
3270{
3271 struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc = &per_cpu(cpu_hw_events, cpu);
3272
3273 if (x86_pmu.extra_regs || x86_pmu.lbr_sel_map) {
3274 cpuc->shared_regs = allocate_shared_regs(cpu);
3275 if (!cpuc->shared_regs)
3276 goto err;
3277 }
3278
3279 if (x86_pmu.flags & PMU_FL_EXCL_CNTRS) {
3280 size_t sz = X86_PMC_IDX_MAX * sizeof(struct event_constraint);
3281
3282 cpuc->constraint_list = kzalloc(sz, GFP_KERNEL);
3283 if (!cpuc->constraint_list)
3284 goto err_shared_regs;
3285
3286 cpuc->excl_cntrs = allocate_excl_cntrs(cpu);
3287 if (!cpuc->excl_cntrs)
3288 goto err_constraint_list;
3289
3290 cpuc->excl_thread_id = 0;
3291 }
3292
3293 return 0;
3294
3295err_constraint_list:
3296 kfree(cpuc->constraint_list);
3297 cpuc->constraint_list = NULL;
3298
3299err_shared_regs:
3300 kfree(cpuc->shared_regs);
3301 cpuc->shared_regs = NULL;
3302
3303err:
3304 return -ENOMEM;
3305}

3310

3312 msr_set_bit(MSR_IA32_DEBUGCTLMSR,
3313 DEBUGCTLMSR_FREEZE_IN_SMM_BIT);

3320static void intel_pmu_cpu_starting(int cpu)
3321{
3322 struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc = &per_cpu(cpu_hw_events, cpu);
3323 int core_id = topology_core_id(cpu);
3324 int i;
3325
3326 init_debug_store_on_cpu(cpu);
3327 /*
3328 * Deal with CPUs that don't clear their LBRs on power-up.
3329 */
3330 intel_pmu_lbr_reset();
3331
3332 cpuc->lbr_sel = NULL;
3333
3334 if (x86_pmu.version > 1)
3335 flip_smm_bit(&x86_pmu.attr_freeze_on_smi);
3336
3337 if (!cpuc->shared_regs)
3338 return;
3339
3340 if (!(x86_pmu.flags & PMU_FL_NO_HT_SHARING)) {
3341 for_each_cpu(i, topology_sibling_cpumask(cpu)) {
3342 struct intel_shared_regs *pc;
3343
3344 pc = per_cpu(cpu_hw_events, i).shared_regs;
3345 if (pc && pc->core_id == core_id) {
3346 cpuc->kfree_on_online[0] = cpuc->shared_regs;
3347 cpuc->shared_regs = pc;
3348 break;
3349 }
3350 }
3351 cpuc->shared_regs->core_id = core_id;
3352 cpuc->shared_regs->refcnt++;
3353 }
3354
3355 if (x86_pmu.lbr_sel_map)
3356 cpuc->lbr_sel = &cpuc->shared_regs->regs[EXTRA_REG_LBR];
3357
3358 if (x86_pmu.flags & PMU_FL_EXCL_CNTRS) {
3359 for_each_cpu(i, topology_sibling_cpumask(cpu)) {
3360 struct cpu_hw_events *sibling;
3361 struct intel_excl_cntrs *c;
3362
3363 sibling = &per_cpu(cpu_hw_events, i);
3364 c = sibling->excl_cntrs;
3365 if (c && c->core_id == core_id) {
3366 cpuc->kfree_on_online[1] = cpuc->excl_cntrs;
3367 cpuc->excl_cntrs = c;
3368 if (!sibling->excl_thread_id)
3369 cpuc->excl_thread_id = 1;
3370 break;
3371 }
3372 }
3373 cpuc->excl_cntrs->core_id = core_id;
3374 cpuc->excl_cntrs->refcnt++;
3375 }
3376}
3377
3378static void free_excl_cntrs(int cpu)
3379{
3380 struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc = &per_cpu(cpu_hw_events, cpu);
3381 struct intel_excl_cntrs *c;
3382
3383 c = cpuc->excl_cntrs;
3384 if (c) {
3385 if (c->core_id == -1 || --c->refcnt == 0)
3386 kfree(c);
3387 cpuc->excl_cntrs = NULL;
3388 kfree(cpuc->constraint_list);
3389 cpuc->constraint_list = NULL;
3390 }
3391}
3392
3393static void intel_pmu_cpu_dying(int cpu)
3394{
3395 struct cpu_hw_events *cpuc = &per_cpu(cpu_hw_events, cpu);
3396 struct intel_shared_regs *pc;
3397
3398 pc = cpuc->shared_regs;
3399 if (pc) {
3400 if (pc->core_id == -1 || --pc->refcnt == 0)
3401 kfree(pc);
3402 cpuc->shared_regs = NULL;
3403 }
3404
3405 free_excl_cntrs(cpu);
3406
3407 fini_debug_store_on_cpu(cpu);
3408}

3539static __init void intel_clovertown_quirk(void)
3540{
3541 /*
3542 * PEBS is unreliable due to:
3543 *
3544 * AJ67 - PEBS may experience CPL leaks
3545 * AJ68 - PEBS PMI may be delayed by one event
3546 * AJ69 - GLOBAL_STATUS[62] will only be set when DEBUGCTL[12]
3547 * AJ106 - FREEZE_LBRS_ON_PMI doesn't work in combination with PEBS
3548 *
3549 * AJ67 could be worked around by restricting the OS/USR flags.
3550 * AJ69 could be worked around by setting PMU_FREEZE_ON_PMI.
3551 *
3552 * AJ106 could possibly be worked around by not allowing LBR
3553 * usage from PEBS, including the fixup.
3554 * AJ68 could possibly be worked around by always programming
3555 * a pebs_event_reset[0] value and coping with the lost events.
3556 *
3557 * But taken together it might just make sense to not enable PEBS on
3558 * these chips.
3559 */
3560 pr_warn("PEBS disabled due to CPU errata\n");
3561 x86_pmu.pebs = 0;
3562 x86_pmu.pebs_constraints = NULL;
3563}
3564
3565static int intel_snb_pebs_broken(int cpu)
3566{
3567 u32 rev = UINT_MAX; /* default to broken for unknown models */
3568
3569 switch (cpu_data(cpu).x86_model) {
3570 case INTEL_FAM6_SANDYBRIDGE:
3571 rev = 0x28;
3572 break;
3573
3574 case INTEL_FAM6_SANDYBRIDGE_X:
3575 switch (cpu_data(cpu).x86_stepping) {
3576 case 6: rev = 0x618; break;
3577 case 7: rev = 0x70c; break;
3578 }
3579 }
3580
3581 return (cpu_data(cpu).microcode < rev);
3582}
3583
3584static void intel_snb_check_microcode(void)
3585{
3586 int pebs_broken = 0;
3587 int cpu;
3588
3589 for_each_online_cpu(cpu) {
3590 if ((pebs_broken = intel_snb_pebs_broken(cpu)))
3591 break;
3592 }
3593
3594 if (pebs_broken == x86_pmu.pebs_broken)
3595 return;
3596
3597 /*
3598 * Serialized by the microcode lock..
3599 */
3600 if (x86_pmu.pebs_broken) {
3601 pr_info("PEBS enabled due to microcode update\n");
3602 x86_pmu.pebs_broken = 0;
3603 } else {
3604 pr_info("PEBS disabled due to CPU errata, please upgrade microcode\n");
3605 x86_pmu.pebs_broken = 1;
3606 }
3607}

3609static bool is_lbr_from(unsigned long msr)
3610{
3611 unsigned long lbr_from_nr = x86_pmu.lbr_from + x86_pmu.lbr_nr;
3612
3613 return x86_pmu.lbr_from <= msr && msr < lbr_from_nr;
3614}
3615
3616/*
3617 * Under certain circumstances, access certain MSR may cause #GP.
3618 * The function tests if the input MSR can be safely accessed.
3619 */
3620static bool check_msr(unsigned long msr, u64 mask)
3621{
3622 u64 val_old, val_new, val_tmp;
3623
3624 /*
3625 * Read the current value, change it and read it back to see if it
3626 * matches, this is needed to detect certain hardware emulators
3627 * (qemu/kvm) that don't trap on the MSR access and always return 0s.
3628 */
3629 if (rdmsrl_safe(msr, &val_old))
3630 return false;
3631
3632 /*
3633 * Only change the bits which can be updated by wrmsrl.
3634 */
3635 val_tmp = val_old ^ mask;
3636
3637 if (is_lbr_from(msr))
3638 val_tmp = lbr_from_signext_quirk_wr(val_tmp);
3639
3640 if (wrmsrl_safe(msr, val_tmp) ||
3641 rdmsrl_safe(msr, &val_new))
3642 return false;
3643
3644 /*
3645 * Quirk only affects validation in wrmsr(), so wrmsrl()'s value
3646 * should equal rdmsrl()'s even with the quirk.
3647 */
3648 if (val_new != val_tmp)
3649 return false;
3650
3651 if (is_lbr_from(msr))
3652 val_old = lbr_from_signext_quirk_wr(val_old);
3653
3654 /* Here it's sure that the MSR can be safely accessed.
3655 * Restore the old value and return.
3656 */
3657 wrmsrl(msr, val_old);
3658
3659 return true;
3660}

3662static __init void intel_sandybridge_quirk(void)
3663{
3664 x86_pmu.check_microcode = intel_snb_check_microcode;
3665 cpus_read_lock();
3666 intel_snb_check_microcode();
3667 cpus_read_unlock();
3668}

3692static __init void intel_nehalem_quirk(void)
3693{
3694 union cpuid10_ebx ebx;
3695
3696 ebx.full = x86_pmu.events_maskl;
3697 if (ebx.split.no_branch_misses_retired) {
3698 /*
3699 * Erratum AAJ80 detected, we work it around by using
3700 * the BR_MISP_EXEC.ANY event. This will over-count
3701 * branch-misses, but it's still much better than the
3702 * architectural event which is often completely bogus:
3703 */
3704 intel_perfmon_event_map[PERF_COUNT_HW_BRANCH_MISSES] = 0x7f89;
3705 ebx.split.no_branch_misses_retired = 0;
3706 x86_pmu.events_maskl = ebx.full;
3707 pr_info("CPU erratum AAJ80 worked around\n");
3708 }
3709}

3794static ssize_t freeze_on_smi_store(struct device *cdev,
3795 struct device_attribute *attr,
3796 const char *buf, size_t count)
3797{
3798 unsigned long val;
3799 ssize_t ret;
3800
3801 ret = kstrtoul(buf, 0, &val);
3802 if (ret)
3803 return ret;
3804
3805 if (val > 1)
3806 return -EINVAL;
3807
3808 mutex_lock(&freeze_on_smi_mutex);
3809
3810 if (x86_pmu.attr_freeze_on_smi == val)
3811 goto done;
3812
3813 x86_pmu.attr_freeze_on_smi = val;
3814
3815 get_online_cpus();
3816 on_each_cpu(flip_smm_bit, &val, 1);
3817 put_online_cpus();
3818done:
3819 mutex_unlock(&freeze_on_smi_mutex);
3820
3821 return count;
3822}

3861__init int intel_pmu_init(void)
3862{
3863 struct attribute **extra_attr = NULL;
3864 struct attribute **to_free = NULL;
3865 union cpuid10_edx edx;
3866 union cpuid10_eax eax;
3867 union cpuid10_ebx ebx;
3868 struct event_constraint *c;
3869 unsigned int unused;
3870 struct extra_reg *er;
3871 int version, i;
3872 char *name;
3873
3874 if (!cpu_has(&boot_cpu_data, X86_FEATURE_ARCH_PERFMON)) {
3875 switch (boot_cpu_data.x86) {
3876 case 0x6:
3877 return p6_pmu_init();
3878 case 0xb:
3879 return knc_pmu_init();
3880 case 0xf:
3881 return p4_pmu_init();
3882 }
3883 return -ENODEV;
3884 }
3885
3886 /*
3887 * Check whether the Architectural PerfMon supports
3888 * Branch Misses Retired hw_event or not.
3889 */
3890 cpuid(10, &eax.full, &ebx.full, &unused, &edx.full);
3891 if (eax.split.mask_length < ARCH_PERFMON_EVENTS_COUNT)
3892 return -ENODEV;
3893
3894 version = eax.split.version_id;
3895 if (version < 2)
3896 x86_pmu = core_pmu;
3897 else
3898 x86_pmu = intel_pmu;
3899
3900 x86_pmu.version = version;
3901 x86_pmu.num_counters = eax.split.num_counters;
3902 x86_pmu.cntval_bits = eax.split.bit_width;
3903 x86_pmu.cntval_mask = (1ULL << eax.split.bit_width) - 1;
3904
3905 x86_pmu.events_maskl = ebx.full;
3906 x86_pmu.events_mask_len = eax.split.mask_length;
3907
3908 x86_pmu.max_pebs_events = min_t(unsigned, MAX_PEBS_EVENTS, x86_pmu.num_counters);
3909
3910 /*
3911 * Quirk: v2 perfmon does not report fixed-purpose events, so
3912 * assume at least 3 events, when not running in a hypervisor:
3913 */
3914 if (version > 1) {
3915 int assume = 3 * !boot_cpu_has(X86_FEATURE_HYPERVISOR);
3916
3917 x86_pmu.num_counters_fixed =
3918 max((int)edx.split.num_counters_fixed, assume);
3919 }
3920
3921 if (boot_cpu_has(X86_FEATURE_PDCM)) {
3922 u64 capabilities;
3923
3924 rdmsrl(MSR_IA32_PERF_CAPABILITIES, capabilities);
3925 x86_pmu.intel_cap.capabilities = capabilities;
3926 }
3927
3928 intel_ds_init();
3929
3930 x86_add_quirk(intel_arch_events_quirk); /* Install first, so it runs last */
3931
3932 /*
3933 * Install the hw-cache-events table:
3934 */
3935 switch (boot_cpu_data.x86_model) {
3936 case INTEL_FAM6_CORE_YONAH:
3937 pr_cont("Core events, ");
3938 name = "core";
3939 break;
3940
3941 case INTEL_FAM6_CORE2_MEROM:
3942 x86_add_quirk(intel_clovertown_quirk);
3943 case INTEL_FAM6_CORE2_MEROM_L:
3944 case INTEL_FAM6_CORE2_PENRYN:
3945 case INTEL_FAM6_CORE2_DUNNINGTON:
3946 memcpy(hw_cache_event_ids, core2_hw_cache_event_ids,
3947 sizeof(hw_cache_event_ids));
3948
3949 intel_pmu_lbr_init_core();
3950
3951 x86_pmu.event_constraints = intel_core2_event_constraints;
3952 x86_pmu.pebs_constraints = intel_core2_pebs_event_constraints;
3953 pr_cont("Core2 events, ");
3954 name = "core2";
3955 break;
3956
3957 case INTEL_FAM6_NEHALEM:
3958 case INTEL_FAM6_NEHALEM_EP:
3959 case INTEL_FAM6_NEHALEM_EX:
3960 memcpy(hw_cache_event_ids, nehalem_hw_cache_event_ids,
3961 sizeof(hw_cache_event_ids));
3962 memcpy(hw_cache_extra_regs, nehalem_hw_cache_extra_regs,
3963 sizeof(hw_cache_extra_regs));
3964
3965 intel_pmu_lbr_init_nhm();
3966
3967 x86_pmu.event_constraints = intel_nehalem_event_constraints;
3968 x86_pmu.pebs_constraints = intel_nehalem_pebs_event_constraints;
3969 x86_pmu.enable_all = intel_pmu_nhm_enable_all;
3970 x86_pmu.extra_regs = intel_nehalem_extra_regs;
3971
3972 x86_pmu.cpu_events = nhm_events_attrs;
3973

4338 x86_pmu.format_attrs = merge_attr(intel_arch3_formats_attr,
4339 extra_attr);
4340 WARN_ON(!x86_pmu.format_attrs);
4341 }
4342
4343 if (x86_pmu.num_counters > INTEL_PMC_MAX_GENERIC) {
4344 WARN(1, KERN_ERR "hw perf events %d > max(%d), clipping!",
4345 x86_pmu.num_counters, INTEL_PMC_MAX_GENERIC);
4346 x86_pmu.num_counters = INTEL_PMC_MAX_GENERIC;
4347 }
4348 x86_pmu.intel_ctrl = (1ULL << x86_pmu.num_counters) - 1;
4349
4350 if (x86_pmu.num_counters_fixed > INTEL_PMC_MAX_FIXED) {
4351 WARN(1, KERN_ERR "hw perf events fixed %d > max(%d), clipping!",
4352 x86_pmu.num_counters_fixed, INTEL_PMC_MAX_FIXED);
4353 x86_pmu.num_counters_fixed = INTEL_PMC_MAX_FIXED;
4354 }
4355
4356 x86_pmu.intel_ctrl |=
4357 ((1LL << x86_pmu.num_counters_fixed)-1) << INTEL_PMC_IDX_FIXED;
4358
4359 if (x86_pmu.event_constraints) {
4360 /*
4361 * event on fixed counter2 (REF_CYCLES) only works on this
4362 * counter, so do not extend mask to generic counters
4363 */
4364 for_each_event_constraint(c, x86_pmu.event_constraints) {
4365 if (c->cmask == FIXED_EVENT_FLAGS
4366 && c->idxmsk64 != INTEL_PMC_MSK_FIXED_REF_CYCLES) {
4367 c->idxmsk64 |= (1ULL << x86_pmu.num_counters) - 1;
4368 }
4369 c->idxmsk64 &=
4370 ~(~0ULL << (INTEL_PMC_IDX_FIXED + x86_pmu.num_counters_fixed));
4371 c->weight = hweight64(c->idxmsk64);
4372 }
4373 }
4374
4375 /*
4376 * Access LBR MSR may cause #GP under certain circumstances.
4377 * E.g. KVM doesn't support LBR MSR
4378 * Check all LBT MSR here.
4379 * Disable LBR access if any LBR MSRs can not be accessed.
4380 */
4381 if (x86_pmu.lbr_nr && !check_msr(x86_pmu.lbr_tos, 0x3UL))
4382 x86_pmu.lbr_nr = 0;
4383 for (i = 0; i < x86_pmu.lbr_nr; i++) {
4384 if (!(check_msr(x86_pmu.lbr_from + i, 0xffffUL) &&
4385 check_msr(x86_pmu.lbr_to + i, 0xffffUL)))
4386 x86_pmu.lbr_nr = 0;
4387 }
4388
4389 x86_pmu.caps_attrs = intel_pmu_caps_attrs;
4390
4391 if (x86_pmu.lbr_nr) {
4392 x86_pmu.caps_attrs = merge_attr(x86_pmu.caps_attrs, lbr_attrs);
4393 pr_cont("%d-deep LBR, ", x86_pmu.lbr_nr);
4394 }
4395
4396 /*
4397 * Access extra MSR may cause #GP under certain circumstances.
4398 * E.g. KVM doesn't support offcore event
4399 * Check all extra_regs here.
4400 */
4401 if (x86_pmu.extra_regs) {
4402 for (er = x86_pmu.extra_regs; er->msr; er++) {
4403 er->extra_msr_access = check_msr(er->msr, 0x11UL);
4404 /* Disable LBR select mapping */
4405 if ((er->idx == EXTRA_REG_LBR) && !er->extra_msr_access)
4406 x86_pmu.lbr_sel_map = NULL;
4407 }
4408 }
4409
4410 /* Support full width counters using alternative MSR range */
4411 if (x86_pmu.intel_cap.full_width_write) {
4412 x86_pmu.max_period = x86_pmu.cntval_mask >> 1;
4413 x86_pmu.perfctr = MSR_IA32_PMC0;
4414 pr_cont("full-width counters, ");
4415 }
4416
4417 kfree(to_free);
4418 return 0;
4419}

4421/*
4422 * HT bug: phase 2 init
4423 * Called once we have valid topology information to check
4424 * whether or not HT is enabled
4425 * If HT is off, then we disable the workaround
4426 */
4427static __init int fixup_ht_bug(void)
4428{
4429 int c;
4430 /*
4431 * problem not present on this CPU model, nothing to do
4432 */
4433 if (!(x86_pmu.flags & PMU_FL_EXCL_ENABLED))
4434 return 0;
4435
4436 if (topology_max_smt_threads() > 1) {
4437 pr_info("PMU erratum BJ122, BV98, HSD29 worked around, HT is on\n");
4438 return 0;
4439 }
4440
4441 cpus_read_lock();
4442
4443 hardlockup_detector_perf_stop();
4444
4445 x86_pmu.flags &= ~(PMU_FL_EXCL_CNTRS | PMU_FL_EXCL_ENABLED);
4446
